# Chapter 16 — The roster remembers

Every instrument in this book carries a memory it wasn't
built with. The oboe carries the memory of the Baroque suites
that first defined its voice; the tabla carries centuries of
teacher-student transmission from North Indian courts; the
guitar carries the campfire songs, the Mississippi Delta
blues, the Andalusian traditions, and the punk shows the same
body sat inside; the synthesizer carries Cologne studios in
the 1950s and 1960s and Detroit basements in the 1980s and
every producer whose signature patch came from a specific
choice on a specific afternoon. The instrument is a small
object; the roster it belongs to is a large tradition; and
the tradition is what the instrument remembers when it's
played.

An instrument is small. What the instrument knows is
large. That's what you're playing into when you pick it
up. You're not the first player, and if the tradition
holds, you won't be the last.

## What she learned in this book

Sixteen chapters of Instruments closes on a small set of
durable facts:

- Every instrument has a family (chapter 1). Families read
  as a first vocabulary — knowing what family an instrument
  belongs to already tells you a lot about how it will be
  used.

- Every instrument has a physical shape whose choices carry
  history (chapters 2-9 for the classical roster; 11-14 for
  the modern folk and voice families). The instrument you're
  holding was shaped by decisions that go back centuries.

- Every instrument has a set of playing techniques (touched
  in each chapter). The techniques compose. A technique from
  one instrument sometimes crosses to another (fingerpicking
  from classical guitar shows up on ukulele, harp, and even
  bass).

- Every instrument has cross-instrument relationships
  (chapter 10 on families, chapter 15 on arrangement). The
  instrument's role in an ensemble is different from its role
  in a solo. Reading the role is a different skill from
  reading the instrument.

- Every instrument has a vocabulary that carries lineage
  (chapter 13 on Latin percussion, chapter 14 on voice
  traditions). Using the vocabulary right is a way of
  listening to the tradition.

## A small farewell exercise

Consider a single instrument you didn't know before this book
— maybe the Indian tabla (chapter 8), maybe the Japanese
shakuhachi (chapter 5), maybe the mokume-gane craftsman's
tool-tradition mentioned in the vocabulary appendix. Take
five minutes and read one paragraph about it, out loud, in a
voice you'd use to tell a friend. Notice what parts of the
paragraph read as personal — as coming from a person who
holds the instrument in their hands — and what parts read as
encyclopedic. The personal parts are usually the ones worth
keeping. The encyclopedic parts are the ones you'll forget by
tomorrow.

```scheme
;; A small map from instrument -> a person you might learn from
(define teacher-of
  '((tabla       \"Ustad Zakir Hussain, live recordings from 1978-2010\")
    (guitar      \"Any local player who'll give you an hour\")
    (voice       \"A singer in whatever tradition first moved you\")
    (synth       \"The manual + the internet, seriously — synths teach themselves once you sit down\")
    (piano       \"The teacher your grandmother recommended\")
    (drums       \"Whoever's playing at the club you can walk to\")
    (fiddle      \"The oldest player at any bluegrass jam within
                  driving distance\")))

(map car teacher-of)
;; => (tabla guitar voice synth piano drums fiddle)
```

The map is illustrative, not prescriptive. The point is that
every instrument in this book has living teachers, and the
living teachers are the ones who carry the tradition
forward. A book like this one is a starting point; it isn't
the whole thing.

## Cross-book pointer

The instruments you've met here compose with the score
records from *Music*, chapter 11. When she writes a piece
of music, she names the instrument. The instrument is a
symbol pulled from the roster — `'piano`, `'shakuhachi`,
`'tabla`, `'voice`, `'synth-analog-sawtooth`. Each symbol
means an instrument in this book. That symbol-to-book
linkage is what makes her scores read as music rather than
as arbitrary sound events.

## Editorial note — the roster is not closed

New instruments enter the roster. The theremin joined in
1928. The Moog synthesizer joined in 1964. The Roland
TR-808 drum machine joined in 1980. The Novation Circuit
Tracks joined in 2021. Every year a maker somewhere invents
an instrument that finds its players and joins the roster,
and the roster grows.

She reads the roster as it is today. Tomorrow's roster will
be larger. When she meets an instrument she doesn't know,
she does the same thing she does when she meets any object
she doesn't know: she asks what it does, listens to how it
sounds, notices what family it belongs to, and holds the
knowledge lightly until it settles into a shape she can
carry.

The book closes here. The roster remembers you turned every
page. Come back when you need to remember what a fiddle
sounds like, or what tumbao means, or why the cuíca whistles.
The roster will still be here.

Goodnight, roster. Goodnight, reader. Come back and play.
